            <div type="a">
                <column>4</column>
                <head>The Peril and the Remedy</head>
                <origin>New York Freeman's Journal</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>This article calls for peace, notes that the Lincoln administration is
                    incompetent, and warns that those who are profiting from the war will soon find
                    their fortunes reversed.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>6</column>
                <head>Imboden's Command</head>
                <origin>Sentinel</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Imboden</ln>
                        <fn/>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf>General</pf>
                    </name>
                </names>
                <summary>Discusses Imboden's leadership and troop movement in western Virginia, the
                    capture of Cumberland, Maryland, and the fear on the part of the people there
                    when they heard that "Imboden, the Guerilla," was coming.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>6</column>
                <head>Liberality to Pastors</head>
                <origin>Central Presbyterian</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The Old School pastor at Harrisonburg announces that his congregation has
                    suffered perhaps more than any other in the presbytery. In spite of the
                    hardship, his salary has been increased by gifts at various times and most
                    recently almost doubled by a single gift.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>6</column>
                <head>War against Catholics</head>
                <origin>New York Freeman</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Refers to an article in the New York Freeman that discusses "various
                    outrages" by New England soldiers to Roman Catholic priests in the Valley and to
                    Roman Catholic churches in Louisiana. The sufferers have appealed to the
                    archbishops and to any high ranking Catholics in the Lincoln administration to
                    keep the war from becoming one against Catholics.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look>**</look>
            </div>
